ODE IV.

This ode is aa expression of friendship to Septimius, a Roman knight cf high standing. He was a poet and a soldier. He had been a school-sellow, a long-tried and intimate friend of Horace, who here tells him, that, as they had passed the best of their days . together in toils and dangers, he now wishes to retire with him, and to spond the evening os life in tranquillity, either at his own seat ut Tibur, or with Septimius at Tarentum.

ODE V.

There has been some doubt who the Pompey here addressed was, some suppose it to have been Pompeius Varus. But it is pretty generally believed that the address is to Pompeius Grosphus Hc was an early friend and companion ofour poet, and was with him at the battle of Philippi. He also continued in opposition to Au- gustus afterwards. But when the peace was concluded between Sextus Pompey and the Triumvirate, ageneral amnesty was grant· ed to all Pompey’s party. Grosphus, taking advantage of this, re- turned to his friends3 on which occasion Horace addressed this ode to him, hy way of congratulation, which naturally turne ou their common dangers and sufferings in former days.
